My name is Mkrtich Tonoyan, and I am an interdisciplinary artist and cultural manager based in Yerevan, Armenia. I am the founder and, since 2006, have been the co-director of ACOSS - the Armenian Art Centre of Social Studies – an international artist in residence. We are a member of Res Artis Worldwide network of artist residencies and the Microresidence International Network. I have been active in the professional field of contemporary art since graduating from the Academy of Fine Arts in Yerevan in 2002, and I regularly present creative projects and lectures on Armenian culture around the world. In 2010, I was awarded a mobility grant from the Euro Cultural Foundation to research models of artist residencies in the UK. In 2011, I was granted professional development funding from the Open Society Foundation to research artist residencies' management practice in the USA.I am married, and we have four daughters.Our Campaign TeamWe are the ACOSS team, a group of Armenian and international artists committed to supporting and developing contemporary art in Armenia. ACOSS Artist in Residence programThe aim of ACOSS is to support the development of contemporary creativity and to assist local Armenian and international artists and scholars to organize exhibitions, conferences, research projects, seminars, and workshops concerning local art and current political and social situations. Our artist-in-residence program is a platform/meeting point where local and international artists and art professionals connect, develop links, and initiate cross border cultural exchange projects. Since 2006, ACOSS AIR has welcomed over 200 international artists and guests from 40 countries. The ACOSS artist residency program is a long term social practice for me, a piece of my art, where my friends, the community where I am based, and my family are all involved. We meet at an intersection of Armenian hospitality and contemporary art. Here, we regularly collaborate with organizations, internationally to provide cultural exchange opportunities, and locally to develop socially engaged projects supporting social change, particularly in the peripheries and war affected zones of Armenia.Our socially-engaged practiceAs co-director of ACOSS I have initiated and coordinated many social and community development projects in Yerevan, Gyumri, Chambarak, on the Armenian borders, and other places. Projects include: Supporting Integration of Invalids into Society (2012 - 2017), Supporting Education on Border Zones and Supporting Social Integration of Syrian Refugees into New Resettlement Territories. During implementation of such projects we collaborate with many local and international organizations, and several of our visiting artists opt to get involved.Our plan to growAfter 11 amazing years, we are now ready to take the next step in the development of the ACOSS artist residency program. Our current studio is a small space, 38 m/sq, and we want to grow! Finally, after years of trying, last year we were able to purchase a piece of land next to the studio and receive permission from the Yerevan city council to start renovation and expansion of our live/work studios to 200 m/sq - nearly five times more space. Having received permission and approval for our building plan, we've put together a dedicated project team and raised enough money to get the project underway. We started construction last year and built the shell of the new building. However, all funds have been exhausted. With Stage 1 successfully completed, we are now fundraising for Stage 2 to finish all the building work for the permit deadline of May 2018.Since our organization's commencement, we have developed a close international network that has enable ACOSS to thrive in an isolated country. To continue growing, we need your support.What we want to achieveThis is a big project and in my country there is no literarily way to get funding or any kind of sponsorship. We are looking to our international communities to support this initiative and help us reach our goals. Armenia is an isolated, mono ethnic country with a lack of funding support for the arts. We believe Armenia needs a truly international art center to welcome guest to our wonderful country.By increasing the space for our art center we will be able to achieve so much more:
Host up to 6-8 visitors at the same time, creating a real international and interdisciplinary atmosphere for creativity;
Establish an exchange studio, in the ‘microresidency’ model, available for studio exchange programs with other countries;
Host YOU as a contributor who would like to join our network, visit our art space and experience Armenian culture;
One of the rooms will be open also as a rental space for visitors; friends or relative of our visiting artist, or for those who wish to get to know Armenian culture alongside artists in a creative space;
The creativity we encourage doesn’t have boarders. We host artists from around the world to undertake research, production and exhibitions in Armenia;
Develop an educational dimension of ACOSS introducing socially engaged practices as a form of art to our emerging Armenian artists;
Continue to develop our ethos and mission as an international art center based in the community, with strong social impact towards social change;
Develop a self-funding model to keep our independent art institution thriving.
What We NeedWe need support from the international community to reach our goals.Our building total costs including official permits, municipal inspections, materials and labour are $89,500. Over the last 2 years we have raised $42,000 in cash donations towards land purchase and permits, and the building materials required to construct the building shell. All our work thus far has been undertaken with volunteer labour from our neighbours and friends. We are proud to say, the support we have already received has enable us to complete stage 1 of the project.We now need to raise a further $47,500 for the materials to complete stage 2 - to finish the project by May 2018, the deadline for official inspection.Cost breakdown:$ 4,800 - 4000 stones and bricks                           - (price for 1 brick - $ 10)$ 700   - 20 m³ sand                                                         - (price for 1 m³ - $ 35)$ 1,500 - 30 m² tiles                                                         - (price for 1 m² - $ 55)$ 800 - 8 taps and plumbing system                      - (price for 1 tap - $ 100)$ 2,300 - 23 m³ concrete                          - (price for 1 m³ concrete - $ 100)$ 1,500 - 10 ton cement                               - (price for 1 ton cement - $ 150)$ 2000 - 80 m² wooden floor                  - (price for 10 m² parquet - $ 250)$ 1,800 - 6 m³ wood for construction          - (price for 1 m³ wood - $ 300)$ 4,440 - 12 windows                                            - (price for 1 window - $ 370)$ 3,260 - 6 doors                                                        - (price for 1 door  - $ 540)$ 700 - Wire (Electricity system)                - (price for total wiring  - $ 700)$ 1,000 - Equipment (El. system)                - (price for El. system - $ 1000)​$ 1,200 - Plaster, paints, glue for tiles, varnish$ 2000 - Staircase$ 3000 - Heating system$ 4000 - Roof with waterproofing and thermal insulation$ 4,275 - Campaign fee 9 %$ 4,335 - Perks international shipping 10 %$ 3,890 - Contributor Perks 10 %Total - $47,500As much as possible, we are using eco-materials, working to European standards, and encouraging creativity in our processes.What if we don’t reach our goal, or raise even more?!If we don’t reach entire goal of fundraising, we will spend the money raised on the primary construction needs such as concrete or stones, roof insulation, windows etc, and continue with our fundraising.But if we raise more than our goal we will put funds into the next stage of renovations for furniture (beds, chairs, easels, shells for library, tables, kitchen furniture), facilities for a small gallery, a library, and to support artists production process and presentation (projectors, cables, computers, printers, point lights, etc.) and other such essentials. Our window to the worldWe are developing an international art space and our door is always open. ACOSS already appears on the map of the contemporary art landscape, proof that with motivation but limited sources you still can do valuable and noticeable things with great impact. Contributors who join our campaign will also join our network where they can keep supporting creativity and have a space to stay and enjoy art in Armenia any time they visit.Perks of Donating...You could recieve one of our beautiful perks including artworks by Armenian and former resident artists. Perks became a sort of fun part of our campaign. When our neighbors learnt about this perks system and how it is going to work, we keep receiving many, many different things from them to offer to our contributors.You will receive CD or DVD of Armenian traditional and folk music and dance, performed by famous contemporary musician Norayr Kartashyan and Van Project, Andranik Manukyan and Gata band.Get a Gift! Perks from the community.  Get Prints! Original artistic prints by local and international artists.Get an Original Artwork! Original art works (ceramic, oil, bronze) by local and international artists.We will contact you sending full list of available perks to learn about your preference.As a friend of ACOSS, we invite you to stay with us, as an artist in residence, or as our guest, or the opportunity to award a residency to an artist of your choice.As a contributor to this campaign, and in the spirit of Armenian friendship, we offer you the opportunity to be an honorary ‘shareholder’ in our project and a lifetime friend for our art center.And if you visit us in Armenia, we will be guide you to enjoy ancient monuments, share a traditional dinner with an Armenian family, participate in Armenian cultural events, and of course, raise a glass of our famous Armenian brandy.Successful track record with projects like this.Main example is the original studio that we are expanding now. I started building it in 2002 with help of friends, our family and community. Permission giving us to build was temporarily and we didn’t own the land and it was going to be temporarily. It took us 3 years to finish the construction. After finishing main construction work we have been developing it since 2005, each year adding something new on the building interior making it more comfortable for our visiting guests and suitable for small events doing there.2 years ago, when we came to agreement with our government to get the studio permanently, not to use temporarily, to be able to invest there and develop as an professional art space, city municipality before giving us that certificate send to us building inspection group to check the quality of the building. We past the inspection and got the certificate of ownership and permission to use it for public events as well. That means, what we building work we did was in acceptable quality. That’s why that gave us permission to start expanding project and also permit to do main works on the construction by ourselves.Risks & ChallengesIf during building we change the project or design or don’t follow the project plan approved by Yerevan municipality, we run the risk of a big penalty. So we stick closely to the plan! Our permit for building expires by a strict deadline of May 2018, we have to complete the building and pass all inspections by that date.To have the project complete by the deadline we need find necessary budget to finish the construction.  We just will keep trying more campaigns until we get necessary budget and complete the 2nd stage of the project.How else can you help us? Join us in our mission to develop an international cultural exchange space and art center for our local community. Help us with promotion our campaign and follow our progress…If you have any additional questions, don’t hesitate to contact us at: office@acoss.orgJoin to our network and support campaign!ACOSS team
